'''Carels Frères''', or Carels Brothers, was a manufacturer of [[stationary steam engine]]s in [[Ghent]], [[Belgium]]. For instance, in 1909, they supplied a 1200&nbsp;hp tandem compound engine with [[super heater]] to  [[List of mills owned by the Lancashire Cotton Corporation Limited#Other Mills that were owned before 1951|Moston Mill]], a [[cotton mill]] in [[Moston, Greater Manchester|Moston]], North Manchester.<ref>{{Harvnb|Hills|1989|p=251}}</ref> It was their works no 875, with cylinders {{convert|30|and|53|in|mm|0|abbr=on}} bore with a {{convert|3|ft|11+1/4|in|mm|0|abbr=on}} stroke. Developing {{convert|1,200|hp|abbr=on}} at 90 [[Revolutions per minute|rpm]], [[superheated steam]] {{convert|200|psi|kPa|0|abbr=on}} was supplied by Tetlow boilers. The flywheel, {{convert|19|ft|mm|0|abbr=on}} in diameter, was provided with the sixty rope grooves that the full power would have required. The second half of the mill, however, was never completed, and in 1958 electric drives were installed, and the engine was scrapped. 

George Watkins commented that this was typical of continent design. Six or more of Carels' engines were installed in Lancashire mills in the early 20th century.<ref>{{Harvnb|Roberts|1921}}</ref>

